<li id="cite_note-philip_jenkins-quote-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-philip_jenkins-quote_61-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFJenkins2009" class="citation journal cs1">Jenkins, Philip (Spring 2009). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1058&amp;context=mormonhistory">"Letting Go: Understanding Mormon Growth in Africa"</a>. <i>Journal of Mormon History</i>. <b>35</b> (2)<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 16,</span> 2012</span>. <q>For one thing, the relatively late start of LDS expansion—from the late 1970s onwards—meant that the missions still have white faces, decades after other traditions have become thoroughly Africanized</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Mormon+History&amp;rft.atitle=Letting+Go%3A+Understanding+Mormon+Growth+in+Africa&amp;rft.ssn=spring&amp;rft.volume=35&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.aulast=Jenkins&amp;rft.aufirst=Philip&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdigitalcommons.usu.edu%2Fcgi%2Fviewcontent.cgi%3Farticle%3D1058%26context%3Dmormonhistory&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+Mormons" class="Z3988"></span></span>
